<section class="page-hero">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
    <h1>Ruby on Rails is the default.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      I'm Stephen Sawyer, a full-stack Ruby on Rails developer and open source,
      privacy, and security advocate. I have spent 15 years in IT building,
      operating, fixing, and explaining systems that need to survive real users.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="page-section">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        <strong>Ruby and Rails are my default because they let me ship fastest.</strong>
        I use other tools when the problem clearly calls for them, but Rails is
        where I reach first for products, APIs, dashboards, admin surfaces, and
        full-stack web apps that should not need a separate SPA just to feel
        modern.
      </p>
      <p>
        The work I like best has a clear owner, a clear data model, and an
        operating story that can be understood without a vendor diagram. A Rails
        app on infrastructure you control is still one of the fastest ways to
        turn an idea into something durable.
      </p>

      <h2>What I care about</h2>

      <p>
        <strong>Ownership.</strong> I like software that can run on hardware
        you control, with data you can inspect and move when you need to.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Privacy and security.</strong> They are not polish items. They
        shape authentication, data retention, logging, dependency choices, and
        the way a product talks about what it stores.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Boring infrastructure.</strong> I prefer the deployment that
        is easy to explain and easy to recover, not the one that looks
        impressive in a diagram. One box, one service, one redeploy script is
        often the correct answer.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Explicit data models.</strong> Schemas, query paths, and
        storage decisions should make the system easier to reason about, not
        harder. Active Record migrations are the changelog for the application
        as much as Git is.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Open source.</strong> Source code should be available when it
        helps people inspect, adapt, self-host, or recover the tools they rely
        on.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Shipping with discipline.</strong> I value iteration, but not
        chaos. The goal is useful software with complexity that has earned its
        place.
      </p>

      <h2>The stack</h2>

      <p>
        My default web stack is <strong>Ruby on Rails 8</strong> with
        <strong>Hotwire</strong> (Turbo + Stimulus) over import maps,
        <strong>Tailwind CSS</strong> for utility classes, and
        <strong>Propshaft</strong> as the asset pipeline. I lean on the Solid
        family — Solid Queue, Solid Cache, and Solid Cable — so a small Rails
        app does not need a Redis just to do background jobs and caching.
      </p>

      <p>
        For data, I default to <strong>SQLite</strong> for products that fit
        on one box and <strong>PostgreSQL</strong> when the product is meant
        to grow. Either way, I want the schema to be explicit and the data
        flow easy to trace.
      </p>

      <p>
        On the frontend, Rails owns rendering. Hotwire turns most of what
        people reach for SPAs to do into server-rendered partials with small
        Stimulus controllers around them. I add JavaScript only when the
        product clearly benefits from it.
      </p>

      <p>
        This site itself runs on an Ubuntu VM as a Rails 8 app behind Caddy,
        with Cloudflare in front. That deployment shape says a lot about how
        I like to work: simple, inspectable, and dependable.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
